The modules are loaded in lexicographical order, and I've arranged them to ensure smooth and lightweight switching between themes.

Only files ending in .sh will be loaded; those ending in .disabled are not.

For example, if you use the Xfce terminal and want its color scheme to change with the theme, you'll need to rename the file 19-xfce-terminal.disabled to 19-xfce-terminal.sh.

This attempts to work similarly to Matugen/Pywal, except there they're called template files, and here I've called them modules... I don't know why.

And they work by using the colors set in theme-config.bash located within each theme.

These are shell scripts, and by leveraging that, within each script (module), configurations for the apps are generated/overwritten. The signal to reset the configuration can also be sent from within the same script (depending on the app, of course).

This is what would be called hooks in Matugen.

-----

For example, the module for changing the Ghostty terminal's color scheme generates the theme template file in the script, using the color variables set in theme-config.bash.

It then generates and overwrites the Ghostty theme, and the command `pkill -USR2 -x ghostty` is sent, which resets the Ghostty configuration and changes the colors on the fly.

